    "summary": "Puntland President Said Abdullahi Deni addressed rumors of a shutdown at Bossaso Port, stating operations including livestock exports and fuel imports continue without interruption, and urged the public and businesses to ignore false claims.",
    "content": "Puntland President Said Abdullahi Deni has spoken firmly about the current situation at Bossaso Port, countering widespread reports that the key maritime facility has ceased operations. In a statement, Deni asserted that the port is functioning normally and that there has been no disruption to essential activities, including the export of livestock and the delivery of fuel supplies. He categorically denied allegations that Bossaso Port is completely closed, calling such reports unfounded.\n\nThe president's remarks come amid heightened public concern over the port's status, which serves as a vital economic lifeline for Puntland and the wider Somali region. Bossaso Port handles a significant portion of livestock exports, a key source of revenue and livelihood for many Somali families, as well as fuel imports that are critical for transportation and energy needs. Any prolonged shutdown would have severe ripple effects on trade and daily life.\n\nDeni emphasized that livestock shipments are departing as scheduled and that fuel tankers are unloading without interruption. He did not provide details on the origin of the closure rumors but urged the business community and the general public to rely only on official information from government sources. His statement appears aimed at stabilizing market confidence and preventing panic among traders and consumers.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, who often send remittances and invest in local enterprises tied to port activities, this assurance matters. Bossaso Port is a major hub for the movement of goods and people between Somalia and the Gulf states, and any instability there can disrupt supply chains that diaspora members depend on for trade or family support. Deni's clarification may help alleviate concerns about potential disruptions to these flows.\n\nThe port has faced periodic challenges, including security incidents and political disputes, but has generally remained operational. Deni's firm denial suggests that recent rumors are not based on current realities, though the situation continues to be monitored by local stakeholders and international partners.\n\nRead the original report from Goobjoog here: https://goobjoog.com/2026/07/15/madaxweyne-deni-oo-si-kulul-uga-hadlay-xaaladda-dekedda-boosaaso-digniinna-u-diray-ganacsatada-iyo-shacabka/",
