    "content": "Local leaders in Kenya’s North Eastern region have called on the national government to reopen the border with Somalia at Liboi, arguing that its extended closure has severely impacted livelihoods, stifled economic growth, and reduced state revenues. The appeal came from a coalition of county officials and community representatives who emphasized the border’s historical role in cross-border trade.\n\nThe border has been shut since 2011 as part of security measures linked to the fight against Al-Shabaab. While the closure was intended to curb militant movement and illicit trade, critics say it has disproportionately affected local communities who depend on commerce with Somalia. Traders have been forced to use informal routes, increasing costs and security risks.\n\nThe leaders highlighted that the closure has not only diminished household incomes but also deprived the government of customs duties and taxes. They argued that a controlled reopening, with enhanced surveillance and biometric screening, could restore legitimate trade while mitigating security concerns.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, the border issue resonates deeply. Many diaspora members maintain business and family ties across the border, and its reopening could facilitate easier movement of goods, remittances, and investment. The call also underscores broader debates about balancing security with economic integration in the Horn of Africa.\n\nRead the original report from Horseed Media here: https://horseedmedia.net/leaders-urge-kenya-to-reopen-somalia-border-to-boost-trade/423733/",
